1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
 One example is the famous story of Nestorius, who was declared a heretic at one of the early councils of the churches, because he couldn't make it, he couldn't get there in time, his church couldn't send representatives, they're dealing in three different languages, he said something, wrote something in one document that was a bit ambiguous about the nature of Christ, but all of his other writing is so classical, so orthodox, and shows that what he said here might have been, you know, a twist of words or something like that.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:59,980
 Well, the council having only one sentence said, heretic, gone, done. Having now resource to all of his stuff, the churches, as it were, reintegrated in the stories into the orthodox community, the warm relations between the churches that were, that considered themselves a story of churches and all that. Well, that's the research that you can do quickly, go through all of his literature, arrive at something. We had another girl here from Syria. She was studying manuscripts.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 And she discovered that one manuscript that had been attributed to a certain author, was not, could not have been his, it had to be someone else. And she could tell by the quality of the language, and then even date things within the text.

4
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:26,360
 Well, again, it was the digitized process that allowed her to see that quickly, rather than having to read through 400 books and go to Paris and go to different countries and compare the volumes.

5
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:46,200
 Fr. David, Matthew, it's a real pleasure to be with you this morning. We're here in Rome as we get ready to launch the Alexandria Digitization Hub, which is a huge project that you guys have been working on for a very long time.

6
00:01:46,200 --> 00:01:53,860
 Fr. David, if I may begin with you, can you share the genesis of that project and your collaboration with Matthew?

7
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:03,980
 Sure. It's a series of births, in a certain sense. It didn't start out as one idea, and then we were moving the train out of the station to arrive at another location.

8
00:02:03,980 --> 00:02:14,660
 For us, the library of the Orientalia, the Pontifical Oriental Institute, is unique in the world. There's no library anywhere that covers all of the Eastern churches.

9
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:20,960
 So, the Eastern churches, which come out of Constantinople, the first church in Jerusalem is an Eastern church, and so on.

10
00:02:20,960 --> 00:02:30,040
 So, our library covers all of the churches, and when you say it covers all of the churches, it means it covers languages, it covers history, it covers politics.

11
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:36,560
 Very often, the first thing that was written down was the Bible in another language, or translated.

12
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:43,280
 When missionaries went from one country to another, they had to translate the Bible, they had to structure even the alphabet in different languages.

13
00:02:43,280 --> 00:02:49,040
 So, the Bible's become great sources of language, language development and structure and all.

14
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:57,220
 So, we have quite a number of academics, researchers that come to the Orientali to use the library, the resources of the library.

15
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:06,960
 We have students, it's basically a graduate school, but the concern was not many can come to Rome for a week or a month and use the resources.

16
00:03:06,960 --> 00:03:10,560
 Isn't there a way to make these resources more available?

17
00:03:10,560 --> 00:03:17,480
 And we're talking about a geographical area from Russia to Ethiopia, from southern Italy to southern India.

18
00:03:17,480 --> 00:03:23,520
 That's where the Eastern churches are, but even Western churches, bishops, scholars are interested in these resources.

19
00:03:24,260 --> 00:03:32,660
 So, my first interest was to digitize the books, get the books online for our students, our past students, for researchers, for scholars.

20
00:03:32,660 --> 00:03:39,440
 We could even have a combined thing online of several scholars studying a manuscript, that would be an excellent thing.

21
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:41,980
 We have perhaps 500 manuscripts in the library.

22
00:03:41,980 --> 00:03:44,060
 So, that's how it began.

23
00:03:44,060 --> 00:03:48,860
 And we found some friends and benefactors, much of it through Matthew's help and inspiration.

24
00:03:48,860 --> 00:03:52,040
 People came here, sent big scanners.

25
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,880
 People came from New York, experts in digitizing, and began the process of digitizing our own publications.

26
00:03:58,880 --> 00:04:01,180
 And it was kind of magical.

27
00:04:01,180 --> 00:04:04,440
 Like, in a certain sense, it was simple what they were doing.

28
00:04:04,440 --> 00:04:12,180
 High-density photographs of everything they were digitizing, 600 dpi, we could reduce to PDFs and make them available.

29
00:04:12,900 --> 00:04:22,260
 But immediately, there was the question, it would be nice if these could be researched by Word and not just pulling down a book or pulling down an article.

30
00:04:22,260 --> 00:04:29,560
 So, as we went on digitizing, we bought a scanner, we got another scanner, and we had two people hired to scan more and more books.

31
00:04:29,780 --> 00:04:38,720
 And then, we were looking initially at one set of software that was being developed that would allow researchers to do research on a manuscript.

32
00:04:39,340 --> 00:04:44,220
 But it was really with the arrival of AI that transformed our possibilities.

33
00:04:44,220 --> 00:04:52,340
 So, first, getting the text off of a PDF onto a computer language that could be easily researched by Word without errors.

34
00:04:53,160 --> 00:04:59,820
 But then, our library has, I don't know if it has 20 or 30 languages in it, ancient languages, modern languages.

35
00:04:59,820 --> 00:05:04,080
 And so, if you want to research something, you want to cross the languages.

36
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:07,920
 So, we might have the works of John Chrysostom in four different languages.

37
00:05:07,920 --> 00:05:10,400
 And even that has a value for scholars.

38
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:13,460
 How do they translate this word into another language?

39
00:05:13,460 --> 00:05:21,280
 Again, when you look at history, the arguments over the interpretations of the nature of Jesus, of the creeds,

40
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:26,720
 A word like person in English, in Italian, sounds pretty straightforward.

41
00:05:26,720 --> 00:05:31,560
 But the word persona in Greek means, it can mean the mask that you wear in a play.

42
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:34,320
 So, is that the best translation to make?

43
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:41,420
 So, you see the debates of scholars from 1,000, 1,500 years ago trying to deal with these changes.

44
00:05:41,420 --> 00:05:48,060
 Well, again, to be able to put these things online, to use AI technology so that you're vectorized,

45
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:51,460
 you're looking for concepts rather than words in one language.

46
00:05:51,780 --> 00:06:02,480
 So, you take the word nature or person and conceptually you translate that into all of the languages that are available to the AI program and you search through the entire library.

47
00:06:03,160 --> 00:06:07,440
 So, the richness for research and for analysis is really quite extraordinary.

48
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:08,380
 Wow.

49
00:06:08,380 --> 00:06:09,900
 That's so inspiring.

50
00:06:09,900 --> 00:06:17,900
 And then, Matthew, when Father David came in with this goal of digitizing the patrimony of the church

51
00:06:17,900 --> 00:06:23,440
 and making the content and the books available from the Orient High to the students around the world,

52
00:06:23,440 --> 00:06:26,900
 what were some of the technical challenges that you faced?

53
00:06:26,900 --> 00:06:32,640
 Well, I mean, I think when we started the project, we weren't thinking so big as like the patrimony of the church.

54
00:06:32,640 --> 00:06:35,380
 I mean, that's something that we now are focused more on.

55
00:06:35,460 --> 00:06:40,720
 But, yeah, initially it was just, let's just try and make sure that these resources in the Eastern church are made more available.

56
00:06:40,720 --> 00:06:43,980
 And then, you know, there was always the idea that if it worked, then we could expand it.

57
00:06:43,980 --> 00:06:46,600
 There were a bunch of technical challenges.

58
00:06:46,840 --> 00:06:53,100
 I mean, you know, one is the books themselves and, you know, Father David can speak more to this than I can.

59
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:56,680
 But, you know, many of these books were very different from each other, right?

60
00:06:56,680 --> 00:07:01,320
 Some had very delicate bindings, you know, some of the more modern books, not so much.

61
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,520
 Some of them are very large books, some of them are very small.

62
00:07:03,520 --> 00:07:07,760
 And so, you know, as much as possible, you want the robot to do most of the work here, right?

63
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:11,320
 With the arm, which, you know, the robot arm, which turns the pages and does the scanning for you.

64
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:15,520
 So, we're trying to automate the process as much as possible, kind of reduce the human in the loop

65
00:07:15,520 --> 00:07:18,120
 and just to allow us to increase the rate at which we're scanning.

66
00:07:18,120 --> 00:07:24,800
 But obviously, you know, every time you change the book out, you have to kind of redial in, you know, the robot

67
00:07:24,800 --> 00:07:27,480
 so it understands what kind of text it's working with so it can effectively turn the pages.

68
00:07:27,480 --> 00:07:29,620
 So, I know that was a challenge.

69
00:07:29,620 --> 00:07:35,800
 And I know that the two lovely women who work in there have become something of experts at kind of sizing up books

70
00:07:35,800 --> 00:07:37,540
 and learning how to dial in the robot.

71
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:42,240
 So, there's still very much like a collaboration between, you know, the robots and the human beings at this stage.

72
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:48,580
 But, you know, the hope is that we'll be able to figure out new ways and deliver kind of new technologies into the hub,

73
00:07:48,580 --> 00:07:50,620
 which will allow for further and further automation.

74
00:07:50,620 --> 00:07:55,380
 So, we're less dependent upon people, you know, in this process and that will allow us to scan more.

75
00:07:55,380 --> 00:07:59,240
 So, I would say that would be one technical challenge that continues to this day.

76
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:01,900
 I will just say that we're starting to look at some interesting approaches.

77
00:08:01,900 --> 00:08:05,860
 I'm sure some people may have seen some articles about how laser technologies and, you know,

78
00:08:05,860 --> 00:08:10,640
 kind of like CT scanning are being used to kind of see through books and especially like manuscripts,

79
00:08:10,640 --> 00:08:13,980
 which are very delicate, right, which they're afraid to kind of open up for the purposes of scanning.

80
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:16,840
 And so, there's new technologies on the scene, I think, that show a lot of promise,

81
00:08:16,840 --> 00:08:21,420
 which would allow us to scan the books without actually having to necessarily open them up and turn the pages,

82
00:08:21,420 --> 00:08:22,920
 which in some cases could damage them.

83
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:25,460
 So, I think the future is very bright for digitization.

84
00:08:25,460 --> 00:08:31,760
 I'd say that the second kind of biggest challenge was, and fellow David kind of spoke to it,

85
00:08:31,760 --> 00:08:35,880
 is how do we extract the information from the pages and then make sure that,

86
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:41,160
 because, you know, OCR, optical character recognition, which is something anyone uses Adobe PDF,

87
00:08:41,160 --> 00:08:46,880
 yeah, is familiar with because it's what allows you to take an image and then allow it to select the text, right?

88
00:08:46,880 --> 00:08:52,200
 That's because Adobe programs, you know, run this optical character recognition on it, but it's a bit flaky, right?

89
00:08:52,260 --> 00:08:56,580
 So, if you were to go in and, like, copy all the text from my PDF document, typically, and paste it into a text,

90
00:08:56,580 --> 00:08:57,940
 it's a bit of a mess, right?

91
00:08:57,940 --> 00:08:59,540
 There can be all kinds of weird characters in there.

92
00:08:59,540 --> 00:09:00,280
 There's no formatting.

93
00:09:00,280 --> 00:09:04,420
 And I'm talking about, like, kind of, you know, these are kind of more simpler problems.

94
00:09:04,420 --> 00:09:07,100
 For more complex text, there can be all kinds of artifacts and things.

95
00:09:07,100 --> 00:09:10,760
 And so, one of the human-in-the-loop challenges was that somebody had to go,

96
00:09:10,760 --> 00:09:14,220
 as they were trying to extract information from the PDF, and clean it up.

97
00:09:14,220 --> 00:09:15,760
 You had to kind of clean up all the noise.

98
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:20,380
 And in many cases, you had to kind of label the text, you know, what's a header, like, what's a footnote.

99
00:09:20,380 --> 00:09:21,860
 You kind of had to put that information in.

100
00:09:22,260 --> 00:09:26,060
 And you had to do all this labeling before you kind of would go through this process of then, like, digitizing it.

101
00:09:26,060 --> 00:09:31,000
 And I say digitizing kind of in a classical sense, not in the AI sense.

102
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:36,560
 And so, what we were trying to figure out is, is there a way that we could run this extraction

103
00:09:36,560 --> 00:09:44,220
 and basically bring AI into the game so it could actually handle all the cleanup, all the labeling of, you know, the text,

104
00:09:44,220 --> 00:09:49,520
 and then also handle automatically this process of converting it from first to kind of vector embeddings,

105
00:09:49,520 --> 00:09:52,720
 which kind of makes this text language agnostic for people to query.

106
00:09:53,140 --> 00:09:57,800
 And then finally, to a format called TEI, which is like an archiving standard, which is kind of a rich metadata format.

107
00:09:57,800 --> 00:10:03,880
 This is all to say that this whole process of figuring this out was something that we felt if we could crack this

108
00:10:03,880 --> 00:10:08,000
 and have AI do this part of the job, this would allow us to significantly speed up digitization,

109
00:10:08,000 --> 00:10:12,480
 mainly because there's a lot of scanned content around the world, scanned for archival purposes,

110
00:10:12,480 --> 00:10:16,260
 but there's never been extraction run on it, which means you couldn't really effectively query it.

111
00:10:16,260 --> 00:10:23,200
 So, if we figured if we could be focused here on this particular problem, this could allow us to unlock all those PDFs,

112
00:10:23,200 --> 00:10:25,500
 which is just kind of sitting around for storage purposes.

113
00:10:25,500 --> 00:10:28,760
 And today, we've been able to pretty much automate that process.

114
00:10:28,760 --> 00:10:30,260
 That's extraordinary.

115
00:10:30,260 --> 00:10:37,680
 And, Father David, of course, the library is at the center of the university and the educational programs

116
00:10:37,680 --> 00:10:39,340
 that your students from around the world are coming.

117
00:10:39,340 --> 00:10:47,420
 How has this project impacted their studies, like making these texts available for students who, for whatever reason,

118
00:10:47,420 --> 00:10:49,960
 might not be able to attend class or come to Rome physically?

119
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:55,160
 How has this digital documentation interacted with them?

120
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,380
 And also, where do you see this going?

121
00:10:57,380 --> 00:10:59,480
 How do you see this impacting their studies in the future?

122
00:10:59,480 --> 00:11:05,660
 Well, one of the things that we had to consider quickly was pedagogy,

123
00:11:06,400 --> 00:11:10,360
 because obviously a concern would be plagiarizing, which is always a concern anyway.

124
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:13,860
 But now, you can cover your plagiarizing pretty quickly.

125
00:11:13,860 --> 00:11:22,800
 So, one of the concerns of the Vatican, which heads all universities that have a Catholic name on them,

126
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:27,780
 are under the general auspices of the Dicastery for Education at the Vatican.

127
00:11:28,540 --> 00:11:32,380
 And it tries to oversee and promote certain aspects of education.

128
00:11:32,380 --> 00:11:38,540
 And one that it likes to guarantee is interpersonal stuff, so that not everything is online,

129
00:11:38,540 --> 00:11:41,940
 not everything is at distance, not everything is through your computer screen,

130
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:48,440
 because there is something that a mother communicates to a child that a book on mothering doesn't communicate to a child.

131
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:51,760
 So, and questions and answers, that kind of interaction.

132
00:11:51,760 --> 00:11:58,880
 Well, what this process did was it made it more important to have more meetings between professors and students.

133
00:11:58,880 --> 00:12:02,620
 So, a student would present their doctoral project, their doctoral proposal.

134
00:12:02,620 --> 00:12:04,640
 And that's a fairly articulate process.

135
00:12:04,640 --> 00:12:06,840
 They have to have a bibliography and a direction to go.

136
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:09,800
 A board of professors sit with the student.

137
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:12,040
 They work it out, approve it, or change it, whatever.

138
00:12:12,040 --> 00:12:17,160
 Then the student has to return after the first piece of research and say,

139
00:12:17,160 --> 00:12:21,180
 if the student is writing in Italian and you know the quality of the person's Italian,

140
00:12:21,180 --> 00:12:23,420
 and now the student is writing like Dante.

141
00:12:23,420 --> 00:12:27,440
 Knowing the student, you know what's happened.

142
00:12:27,440 --> 00:12:31,760
 So, when you have regular meetings, instead of waiting until the dissertation is finished,

143
00:12:31,760 --> 00:12:35,460
 you can challenge the student with the content that the student has written.

144
00:12:35,460 --> 00:12:36,840
 Do you understand what you've written?

145
00:12:37,060 --> 00:12:38,420
 What are the implications of this?

146
00:12:38,420 --> 00:12:43,300
 And so, you have a more interpersonal focus in the educational process,

147
00:12:43,300 --> 00:12:44,780
 and the student has to defend.

148
00:12:44,780 --> 00:12:51,320
 Even if they've used whatever AI tools, the student has to defend what he or she has written.

149
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:56,200
 So, oddly, the technology has improved human communication,

150
00:12:56,200 --> 00:13:02,140
 which is the last thing we always expect with AI and digitization.

151
00:13:03,180 --> 00:13:11,060
 Another benefit that it offers is there have been mistakes made academically in the past

152
00:13:11,060 --> 00:13:19,620
 for clear reasons that can now be researched in a more clear, concise, and quick way.

153
00:13:19,860 --> 00:13:23,780
 One example is the famous story of Nestorius,

154
00:13:23,780 --> 00:13:27,700
 who was declared a heretic at one of the early councils of the churches

155
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:29,300
 because he couldn't make it.

156
00:13:29,300 --> 00:13:30,540
 He couldn't get there in time.

157
00:13:30,540 --> 00:13:32,180
 His church couldn't send representatives.

158
00:13:32,180 --> 00:13:33,980
 They're dealing in three different languages.

159
00:13:33,980 --> 00:13:36,680
 He said something, wrote something in one document

160
00:13:36,680 --> 00:13:39,260
 that was a bit ambiguous about the nature of Christ.

161
00:13:39,580 --> 00:13:44,800
 But all of his other writing is so classical, so orthodox,

162
00:13:44,800 --> 00:13:47,820
 and shows that what he said here might have been, you know,

163
00:13:47,820 --> 00:13:49,540
 a twist of words or something like that.

164
00:13:49,540 --> 00:13:52,760
 Well, the council having only one sentence said,

165
00:13:52,760 --> 00:13:54,460
 heretic, gone, done.

166
00:13:54,460 --> 00:13:57,520
 Having now resourced to all of this stuff,

167
00:13:57,520 --> 00:14:01,940
 the churches, as it were, reintegrated in Nestorius

168
00:14:01,940 --> 00:14:04,220
 into the orthodox community,

169
00:14:04,220 --> 00:14:06,360
 the warm relations between the churches

170
00:14:06,360 --> 00:14:09,980
 that considered themselves Nestorian churches and all that.

171
00:14:09,980 --> 00:14:12,240
 Well, that's a research that you can do quickly,

172
00:14:12,240 --> 00:14:13,800
 both through all of his literature,

173
00:14:13,800 --> 00:14:15,160
 arrive at something.

174
00:14:15,160 --> 00:14:17,300
 We had another girl here from Syria.

175
00:14:17,300 --> 00:14:19,220
 She was studying manuscripts,

176
00:14:19,220 --> 00:14:21,560
 and she discovered that one manuscript

177
00:14:21,560 --> 00:14:24,800
 that had been attributed to a certain author

178
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:28,480
 could not have been his.

179
00:14:28,480 --> 00:14:29,980
 It had to be someone else.

180
00:14:29,980 --> 00:14:32,220
 and she could tell by the quality of the language

181
00:14:32,220 --> 00:14:34,760
 and then even date things within the text.

182
00:14:34,760 --> 00:14:37,180
 Well, again, it was the digitized process

183
00:14:37,180 --> 00:14:39,440
 that allowed her to see that quickly

184
00:14:39,440 --> 00:14:42,140
 rather than having to read through 400 books

185
00:14:42,140 --> 00:14:44,600
 and go to Paris and go to different countries

186
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:46,100
 and compare the volumes.

187
00:14:46,100 --> 00:14:48,080
 That's extraordinary.

188
00:14:48,080 --> 00:14:51,660
 And then, Matthew, as we get ready to, you know,

189
00:14:51,660 --> 00:14:54,640
 start to really maximize the hub

190
00:14:54,640 --> 00:14:55,880
 as the scanners come in

191
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:57,420
 and as they start to really,

192
00:14:57,420 --> 00:14:58,460
 the work comes underway,

193
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:00,220
 what is that going to look like?

194
00:15:00,220 --> 00:15:01,340
 Can you break it down

195
00:15:01,340 --> 00:15:02,860
 and kind of walk us through those steps?

196
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:04,340
 Sure.

197
00:15:04,340 --> 00:15:08,840
 I mean, so we embarked on this kind of proof of concept,

198
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:10,560
 you know, I think it's almost a couple of years now.

199
00:15:10,560 --> 00:15:12,240
 So we had this kind of robot scanner.

200
00:15:12,240 --> 00:15:13,720
 We had this kind of high-end manual scanner

201
00:15:13,720 --> 00:15:14,780
 for more delicate manuscripts.

202
00:15:14,780 --> 00:15:17,100
 And we really just want to kind of push the technology

203
00:15:17,100 --> 00:15:18,760
 to see how far we could get with it.

204
00:15:18,760 --> 00:15:19,440
 And so, I mean,

205
00:15:19,440 --> 00:15:22,340
 we still think there's a long way for the hardware to go,

206
00:15:22,580 --> 00:15:24,820
 but certainly the robo scanner is helpful.

207
00:15:24,820 --> 00:15:27,820
 So we said, okay, so it's working.

208
00:15:27,820 --> 00:15:30,780
 We need to figure out this whole digitization process.

209
00:15:30,780 --> 00:15:32,200
 And that's kind of the last year

210
00:15:32,200 --> 00:15:33,040
 what we've been really working on

211
00:15:33,040 --> 00:15:34,520
 is how far can we push AI

212
